{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17409656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17409656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T04:58:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T04:56:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260860"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T04:55:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T05:01:27+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"new","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":3,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T05:00:17+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2703"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.28,0.07,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"656"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy is admitted to the orthopaedic ward after fracturing his tibia in a soccer game yesterday. He had surgery last night and has since been started on a patient-controlled analgesia (PCA) pump with fentanyl which is still working. He has a medical history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and is on regular basal-bolus insulin, which has been prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nurse pages for medical assistance because he starts acting strangely and is drowsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 124/min, blood pressure 95/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO2 99% on 15 L/min oxygen via non-rebreather mask, and temperature 36.0\u00b0C. He is unresponsive to verbal or painful stimuli. His blood glucose level is 2.0 mmol/L. He is sweaty to touch and looks pale. He has intact plaster over his left lower leg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcutaneous insulin injection","Oral dextrose gel","IM glucagon injection","IM naloxone injection","IV 10% glucose at 2 mL/kg"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a patient with severe hypoglycaemia, defined as a blood glucose level \u0026lt;4 mmol/L, who is unconscious. Urgent management is required to correct this potentially life-threatening condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003EIV 10% glucose at 2 mL/kg\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the recommended first-line treatment for severe hypoglycaemia in unconscious patients according to the Advanced Paediatric Life Support (APLS) guidelines. While the patient\u0027s IV access has tissued, re-establishing IV access should be prioritized to administer this treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous insulin\u003C/strong\u003E injection would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous in this scenario, as it would further lower the patient\u0027s already critically low blood glucose level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral dextrose gel\u003C/strong\u003E is not suitable for unconscious patients due to the risk of aspiration, however this is a relative contraindication and if this is the only option in an out of hospital setting it could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIM glucagon injection\u003C/strong\u003E can be an alternative treatment for severe hypoglycaemia when IV access is not available. However, it is less effective than IV glucose, especially after prolonged periods of fasting, and its onset of action is slower.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIM naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E injection is used for opioid toxicity. While the patient is on a fentanyl PCA, his respiratory rate and oxygen saturation do not suggest opioid-induced respiratory depression. The primary issue here is hypoglycaemia, not opioid toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering IV glucose, the patient\u0027s blood glucose level should be rechecked within 10-15 minutes. If the patient regains consciousness, oral carbohydrates should be given. If hypoglycaemia persists, the IV glucose dose may need to be repeated. Once stabilized, it\u0027s crucial to investigate and address the cause of the hypoglycaemic episode, which may involve adjusting the patient\u0027s insulin regimen and ensuring adequate caloric intake while on the PCA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypoglycaemia is defined as a blood glucose level \u003C4 mmol/L.","In an alert patient, hypoglycaemia can be managed with fast-acting sugars (lollies, fruit juice).","In an unconscious patient with hypoglycaemia, IV 10% glucose at 2 mL/kg is the recommended first-line treatment as per APLS guidelines."],"references":["Mathew P, Thoppil D. Hypoglycemia. [Updated 2021 Jan 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534841/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-13T16:01:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-13T16:01:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t